Atomic type expressions: type constructor names (Int, String), type
variables (a, b), parenthesised types, tuple types (a, b, c), and list
types [a]. The atomic building blocks for type_application.
@End Reasoning
@Reasoning:
Parses a bare type-constructor / class name (an uppercase-led identifier
lexed as TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR). Used by the deriving-clause parser to read
each derived class name (Eq, Show, ...). The defining grammar position is
"a single capitalized name"; full type application is handled elsewhere by
parse_haskell_type_application.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Reads the current token; when it is a TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR, captures the
lexeme, builds an AST_TYPE_CONSTRUCTOR node carrying the name, advances
past it, and returns the node. When the current token is NOT a
constructor (malformed deriving list), it records a parse error via the
parser's error counter AND force-advances one token before returning 0.
The forced advance is essential: the enclosing deriving loop is a
`While 1` that only breaks on `)` / consumes `,`; without guaranteed
forward progress here a stray token would spin that loop forever
(unbounded-allocation hang). EOF is never advanced past, so the loop's
EOF guard still terminates the parse.
